# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1824-united-states-presidential-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1796, when electors throughout the United States cast their ballots.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first contested American presidential election, the first presidential election in which political parties played a dominant role, and the only presidential election in which a president and vice president were elected from opposing tickets.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent vice president John Adams of the Federalist Party defeated former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent president George Washington having refused a third term in office, the 1796 election became the first U.S. presidential election in which political parties competed for the presidency.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists coalesced behind Adams and the Democratic-Republicans supported Jefferson, but each party ran multiple candidates.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the electoral rules in place prior to the Twelfth Amendment, the members of the Electoral College each cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The individual with the votes of a majority of electors became president, and the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If there was a tie for first place or no person won a majority, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Also, if there were a tie for second place, the vice presidency, the Senate would hold a contingent election to break the tie.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was a bitter one, with Federalists attempting to identify the Democratic-Republicans with the violence of the French Revolution and the Democratic-Republicans accusing the Federalists of favoring monarchism and aristocracy.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans sought to associate Adams with the policies developed by fellow Federalist Alexander Hamilton during the Washington administration, which they declaimed were too much in favor of Great Britain and a centralized national government.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In foreign policy, Republicans denounced the Federalists over the Jay Treaty, which had established a temporary peace with Great Britain.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Jefferson's moral character, alleging he was an atheist and that he had been a coward during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's supporters also accused Jefferson of being too pro-France; the accusation was underscored when the French ambassador embarrassed the Republicans by publicly backing Jefferson and attacking the Federalists right before the election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the hostility between their respective camps, neither Adams nor Jefferson actively campaigned for the presidency.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was elected president with 71 electoral votes, one more than was needed for a majority.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] He won by sweeping the electoral votes of New England and winning votes from several other swing states, especially the states of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 electoral votes and was elected vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Former governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, a Federalist, finished with 59 electoral votes, while Senator Aaron Burr, a Democratic-Republican from New York, won 30 electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 48 electoral votes were dispersed among nine other candidates.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Several electors cast one vote for a Federalist candidate and one for a Democratic-Republican.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Washington retiring after two terms, both parties sought the presidency for the first time.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Before the ratification of the 12th Amendment in 1804, each elector was to vote for two persons but was not able to indicate which vote was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the recipient of the most electoral votes would become president and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, both parties ran multiple candidates for president, in hopes of keeping one of their opponents from being the runner-up.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These candidates were the equivalent of modern-day running mates, but under the law, they were all candidates for president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, both Adams and Jefferson were technically opposed by several members of their own parties.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The plan was for one of the electors to cast a vote for the main party nominee (Adams or Jefferson) and a candidate besides the primary running mate, thus ensuring that the main nominee would have one more vote than his running mate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists' nominee was John Adams of Massachusetts, the incumbent vice president and a leading voice during the Revolutionary period.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalist leaders viewed Adams, who had twice been elected vice president, as Washington's natural heir.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's main running mate was Thomas Pinckney, a former governor of South Carolina who had negotiated the Treaty of San Lorenzo with Spain.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney agreed to run after the first choice of many party leaders, former governor Patrick Henry of Virginia, declined.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander Hamilton, who competed with Adams for leadership of the party, worked behind the scenes to elect Pinckney over Adams by convincing Jefferson electors from South Carolina to cast their second votes for Pinckney.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton did prefer Adams to Jefferson, and urged Federalist electors to cast their votes for Adams and Pinckney.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans united behind former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson, who had co-founded the party with James Madison and others in opposition to Hamilton's policies.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Democratic-Republicans sought to also unite behind one vice-presidential nominee.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Jefferson's popularity strongest in the South, many party leaders wanted a Northern candidate as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Popular choices included Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina and three New Yorkers: Senator Aaron Burr, Chancellor Robert R.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Livingston, and former governor George Clinton.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in June 1796 and agreed to support Jefferson for president and Burr for vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Tennessee was admitted into the United States after the 1792 election, increasing the Electoral College to 138 electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, electors were to cast votes for two persons for president; the runner-up in the presidential race was elected vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If no candidate won votes from a majority of the Electoral College, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the winner.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Each party intended to manipulate the results by having some of their electors cast one vote for the intended presidential candidate and one vote for someone besides the intended vice-presidential candidate, leaving their vice-presidential candidate a few votes shy of their presidential candidate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] But all electoral votes were cast on the same day, and communications between states were extremely slow at that time, making it very difficult to coordinate which electors were to manipulate their vote for vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, there were rumors that Hamilton had coerced southern electors pledged to Jefferson to give their second vote to Pinckney in hope of electing him president instead of Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning centered in the swing states of New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams and Jefferson won a combined 139 electoral votes from the 138 members of the Electoral College.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept every state north of the Mason–Dixon line except Pennsylvania, though one Pennsylvania elector voted for Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans won the votes of most Southern electors, but the electors of Maryland and Delaware gave a majority of their votes to Federalist candidates, while North Carolina and Virginia each gave Adams one electoral vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, most electors voted for Adams and a second Federalist or for Jefferson and a second Democratic-Republican, but there were several exceptions to this.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] One elector in Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, and two electors cast votes for Washington, who had not campaigned and was not formally affiliated with either party.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney won the second votes from most of the electors who voted for Adams, but 21 electors from New England and Maryland cast their second votes for other candidates, including Chief Justice Oliver Ellsworth.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Those who voted for Jefferson were significantly less united in their second choice, though Burr won a plurality of the Jefferson electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] All eight electors in Pinckney's home state of South Carolina, as well as at least one Pennsylvania elector, cast their ballots for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, Jefferson won 11 votes, but the remaining 13 were spread among six different candidates from both parties.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, most electors voted for Jefferson and Governor Samuel Adams of Massachusetts.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 8, 1797, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Although some contemporary newspapers contested the legal validity of Vermont's electoral votes, no objections against them were raised in congress.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The result was that Adams received 71 electoral votes, one more than required to be elected president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If any two of the three Adams electors in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina had voted with the rest of their states, it would have flipped the election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 votes, nine more than Pinckney, and was elected vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Burr finished in a distant fourth place with 30 votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nine other candidates received the remaining 48 electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If Pinckney had won the second votes of all of the New England electors who voted for Adams, he would have been elected president over Adams and Jefferson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 138 participating electors, 70 voted for Adams and some other candidate and 67 voted for Jefferson and some other candidate; one elector from Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, bringing their respective totals to 71 and 68.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With both parties' electors divided on their choice of a vice president, Jefferson finished second in the electoral vote ahead of Adams' intended running mate, Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, making him vice president-elect.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Compiling reliable popular vote statistics for elections of the First Party System poses a challenge to historians.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Election procedures of the late 18th century differed greatly from those of later campaigns: rather than vote for a presidential candidate, voters chose from candidates running to represent their state in the electoral college.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates for elector did not always advertise a party preference or even for whom they intended to vote; in some districts, candidates from the same party were in direct competition, while in others, inconsistent support for all candidates of a party led states to split their electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These conditions make it difficult or impossible to determine voter intent in some cases.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, some states' returns have not survived to the present day, meaning that national popular vote totals in this article are necessarily incomplete.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The table below calculates each state's popular vote by comparing the vote for the most popular Adams elector to that for the most popular Jefferson elector.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidates for the First Western and Second Middle Districts, Simon Larned and James Winthrop respectively, were not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Larned was a Democratic-Republican and Winthrop was a former Anti-Federalist.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Massachusetts and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The following four years were the only time that the president and vice president were from different parties.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun were later elected president and vice-president as political opponents, but they were both Democratic-Republicans, and while Andrew Johnson, Abraham Lincoln's second vice-president, was a Democrat, Lincoln ran on a combined National Union Party ticket in 1864, not as a strict Republican.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] On January 6, 1797, Representative William L.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Smith of South Carolina presented a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution by which the presidential electors would designate which candidate would be president and which vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] No action was taken on his proposal, setting the stage for the deadlocked election of 1800.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is also the first of only two elections so far in the life of the Republic which elected a presidential term of only 1,460 days rather than 1,461 days (the second was in 1896).
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is because of the Gregorian calendar rule that years ending in “00” but not divisible by 400, are not leap years.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The French foreign minister, Charles Delacroix, wrote that France "must raise up the [American] people and at the same time conceal the lever by which we do so...
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The foreign intrigue France perpetrated was unsuccessful, as Adams won the election with an electoral vote count of 71–68.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A significant factor in thwarting the French efforts was George Washington's Farewell Address, which condemned foreign meddling in America.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 3, 1800.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election in U.S. history to be a rematch, the first election where an incumbent president lost re-election, leading to the first time in modern history where a national government changed hands peaceably following a free election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams had narrowly defeated Jefferson in the 1796 election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the rules of the electoral system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, each member of the Electoral College cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As Jefferson received the second-most votes in 1796, he was elected vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1800, unlike in 1796, both parties formally nominated tickets.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Jefferson and Aaron Burr, while the Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of Adams and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each party formed a plan by which one of their respective electors would vote for a third candidate or abstain so that its preferred presidential candidate (Adams for the Federalists and Jefferson for the Democratic-Republicans) would win one more vote than the party's other nominee.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The chief political issues revolved around the fallout from the French Revolution and the Quasi-War.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists favored a strong central government and close relations with Great Britain.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans favored decentralization to the state governments, and the party attacked the taxes the Federalists imposed.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans also denounced the Alien and Sedition Acts, which the Federalists had passed to make it harder for immigrants to become citizens and to restrict statements critical of the federal government.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans were well organized at the state and local levels, while the Federalists were disorganized and suffered a bitter split between their two major leaders, Adams and Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to historian John Ferling, the jockeying for electoral votes, regional divisions, and the propaganda smear campaigns created by both parties made the election recognizably modern.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] At the end of a long and bitter campaign, Jefferson and Burr each won 73 electoral votes, Adams won 65, and Pinckney won 64.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept New England, the Democratic-Republicans dominated the South, and the parties split the Mid-Atlantic states of New York, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans' assumption that one or more electors in Rhode Island, Vermont, New Jersey, Georgia, Kentucky, or Tennessee would vote for Jefferson and not Burr resulted in a tie, known as the Burr dilemma.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It necessitated a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the terms laid out in the Constitution, the outgoing House of Representatives chose between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Burr was accused of campaigning for the presidency himself in the contingent election despite being a member of Jefferson's party.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each state delegation cast one vote, and a victory in the contingent election required one candidate to win a majority of the state delegations.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither Burr nor Jefferson was able to win on the first 35 ballots of the contingent election, as most Federalist representatives backed Burr and all Democratic-Republican representatives backed Jefferson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton favored Jefferson over Burr, and he convinced several Federalists to switch their support to Jefferson, giving Jefferson a victory on the 36th ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson became the second consecutive incumbent vice president to be elected president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1824 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties used congressional nominating caucuses to formally nominate tickets for the first time.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of incumbent President John Adams of Massachusetts and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney had fought in the American Revolutionary War and later served as the minister to France.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Vice President Thomas Jefferson of Virginia and former Senator Aaron Burr of New York.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had been the runner-up in the previous election and had co-founded the party with James Madison and others, while Burr was popular in the electorally important state of New York.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] While the 1800 election was a re-match of the 1796 election, it ushered in a new type of American politics, a two-party republic and acrimonious campaigning behind the scenes and through the press.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On top of this, the election pitted the "larger than life" Adams and Jefferson, who were formerly close allies turned political enemies.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was bitter and characterized by slander and personal attacks on both sides.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists spread rumors that the Democratic-Republicans were radical atheists who would ruin the country (based on the Democratic-Republican support for the French Revolution).
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1798, George Washington had complained "that you could as soon scrub the blackamoor white, as to change the principles of a professed Democrat; and that he will leave nothing unattempted to overturn the Government of this Country".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, the Democratic-Republicans accused Federalists of subverting republican principles with the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They also accused Federalists of favoring Britain in its war with France in order to promote aristocratic, anti-democratic values.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was attacked by both the opposition Democratic-Republicans and a group of so-called "High Federalists" aligned with Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] "High Federalists" considered Adams too moderate and would have preferred the leadership of Alexander Hamilton instead.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton had apparently grown impatient with Adams and wanted a new president who was more receptive to his goals.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] During Washington's presidency, Hamilton had been able to influence the federal response to the Whiskey Rebellion (which threatened the government's power to tax citizens).
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When Washington announced that he would not seek a third term, the Federalists and Adams regarded himself as next-in-line.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton appears to have hoped in 1796 that his influence within an Adams administration would be as great as or greater than in Washington's.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] By 1800, Hamilton had come to realize that Adams was too independent and thought the Federalist vice presidential candidate, Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina, more suited to serving Hamilton's interests.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In his third sabotage attempt toward Adams, Hamilton quietly schemed to elect Pinckney to the presidency.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Given Pinckney's lack of political experience, he would have been expected to be open to Hamilton's influence.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Hamilton's plan backfired and hurt the Federalist party, particularly after one of his letters, a scathing criticism of Adams that was fifty-four pages long, fell into the hands of a Democratic-Republican and soon after became public.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It embarrassed Adams and damaged Hamilton's efforts on behalf of Pinckney, not to mention speeding Hamilton's own political decline.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The contemporarily unorthodox public campaigning methods employed in 1800 were first employed by Jefferson's running mate and campaign manager, Aaron Burr, who is credited by some historians with inventing the modern electioneering process.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Yet, throughout this entire process, the candidates themselves were conspicuously missing from the campaigning, at least publicly, due to fears that they may otherwise be tagged as "demagogues".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Even a visit John Adams made to Washington was made into a public point of contention.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Partisans on both sides sought any advantage they could find.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In several states, this included changing the process of selecting electors to ensure the desired result.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Georgia, Democratic-Republican legislators replaced the popular vote with selection by the state legislature.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, the Democratic-Republican-controlled legislature switched from electoral districts to a general ticket, a winner-take-all system.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist legislators also switched methods, switching from districts and general tickets to legislature votes in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, respectively.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, the General Assembly was split, with the Democratic-Republican-dominated House wishing to retain the general ticket and the Federalist-controlled Senate wishing to return to the district system, hoping to win at least some electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Eventually, this deadlock was broken by a last-minute compromise between the chambers that gave the Democratic-Republican eight electors and the Federalists seven.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the rejection to change the selection method backfired on the Federalists.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In March 1800, two months before the assembly elections, the Democratic-Republicans attempted to pass a bill that would switch from a legislature vote to electoral districts, hoping they would secure at least a third of the state's seats.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists defeated the measure, believing that they would win control of both chambers and award all of the state's electoral votes to the Federalist nominees.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the April state elections, Aaron Burr's effective mobilization of the vote in New York City led to a reversal of the Federalist majority in the state legislature, providing crucial support for the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In response to the Federalist defeat, Hamilton attempted to get Governor John Jay to call a special session of the outgoing Federalist-dominated New York legislature.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's plan was for the outgoing assembly to pass legislation that would establish the popular election of electors through electoral districts, a strategy almost certain to secure nine or ten of the twelve elector slots for the Federalists.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jay refused to participate in such an underhanded scheme.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist legislature in Connecticut did not change the method of voting but instead passed a "stand up" election law, mandating that all votes be cast publicly and orally, an intimidating procedure that ordinarily favored those in power.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As election day neared, the election was too close to call.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The last state to vote, South Carolina, chose its electors on December 2, and would become key to determining the election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The state elections in mid-October had produced an assembly that was about evenly divided between committed Federalists and Republicans, with 16 unaffiliated representatives who were all strongly pro-Jefferson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Many of the elected Jeffersonians were also supporters of Pinckney, the revered native son of the state.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] If South Carolina's electors gave their votes to Jefferson and Pinckney, then Pinckney would place an electoral vote behind Jefferson, becoming the vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Pinckney stayed loyal to the instructions of his party's caucus and was adamant that any elector who voted for him must also vote for Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With uncommitted legislators not willing to desert Jefferson and Pinckney unwilling to abandon Adams, the uncommitted legislators eventually reluctantly agreed to support Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the United States Constitution as it then stood, each elector cast two votes, and the candidate with a majority of the votes was elected president, with the vice presidency going to the runner-up.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists therefore arranged for one of their Rhode Island electors to vote for John Jay instead of Charles Pinckney to prevent the election from resulting in a tie.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] A letter to Jefferson from Peter Freneau assured him that a member of the Republican delegation from South Carolina would vote for George Clinton instead of Aaron Burr and a report from Georgia indicated that two of its electors would deny Burr their votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, this information proved faulty.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, all of the Democratic-Republican electors cast their votes for both Jefferson and Burr, 73 in all for each of them.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to a provision of the United States Constitution, a tie in a case of this type had to be resolved by the House of Representatives, with each state casting one vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the outgoing House, the Federalists had a majority of 60 seats to 46.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When the electoral ballots were opened and counted on February 11, 1801, the certificate of election from Georgia was different than the others.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Georgia had sent the original oral ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 2004, David Fontana and Bruce Ackerman asserted that Georgia's certificate did not take the constitutionally mandated form of a "List of all the Persons voted for, and of the Number of Votes for each".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They claimed that Vice President Jefferson, who was presiding over the counting of electoral votes in his role as President of the Senate, immediately counted the votes from Georgia as votes for Jefferson and Burr, though they observed that "no objections were raised".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney, and John Jay) in the House of Representatives.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With these votes, the total number of votes for Jefferson and Burr was 73, which gave them a majority of the total, but they were tied.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Holly Brewer, a legal historian, argued that the counting of the Georgia ballot did not support Ackerman and Fontana's theory.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Brewer's arguments helped to influence Vice President Pence's decision to reject the theory that he had such powers, via Judge J.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson and Burr carried every state that had supported the Democratic-Republicans in 1796, made gains in Maryland, and picked up Burr's home state of New York.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the six states choosing electors by some form of popular vote, they won a landslide over Adams and Pinckney, polling 15,846 more votes than the Federalist ticket.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams made gains in Pennsylvania and North Carolina, but these votes were not enough to offset the Democratic-Republican gains elsewhere.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 155 counties and independent cities making returns, Jefferson and Burr won in 115 (74.19%), whereas the Adams ticket carried 40 (25.81%).
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last time that Vermont voted for the Federalists and the last time a Federalist won electoral votes from Pennsylvania.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of two elections contested between people who would at some point serve as vice president, the other being 1968.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 16 states that took part in the 1800 election, six (Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, Rhode Island, Tennessee, and Virginia) used some kind of popular vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Rhode Island and Virginia, voters elected their state's entire Electoral College delegation at large; Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee all used some variation of single-member districts.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the rest, electors were chosen by the state legislature.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Not until the 1836 presidential election would all states have direct popular selection of electors (except South Carolina, which had its state legislature vote for electors until 1868).
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Popular vote records for several states are incomplete, and the returns from Kentucky and Tennessee appear to have been lost; states did not print or issue electoral ballots, and most were issued by newspapers that supported a particular party or candidate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Newspapers are also the main source of voting records in the early 19th century, and frontier states such as Tennessee had few in operation, without any known surviving examples.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee chose each of their electors from specially-drawn single-member districts, the results from which are as follows.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In February 1801, the members of the House of Representatives balloted as states to determine whether Jefferson or Burr would become president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] There were sixteen states, each with one vote; an absolute majority of nine was required for victory.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It was the outgoing House of Representatives, controlled by the Federalist Party, that was charged with electing the new president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was the great enemy of the Federalists, and a faction of Federalist representatives tried to block him and elect Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalists voted for Burr, giving Burr six of the eight states controlled by Federalists.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The seven delegations controlled by Democratic-Republicans all voted for Jefferson, and Georgia's sole Federalist representative also voted for him, giving him eight states.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Vermont delegation was evenly split and cast a blank ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining state, Maryland, had five Federalist representatives to three Democratic-Republicans; one of its Federalist representatives voted for Jefferson, forcing that state delegation also to cast a blank ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Publicly, Burr remained quiet between mid-December 1800 and mid-February 1801, when the electoral votes were counted.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Behind the scenes, he faced mounting pressure from within the party to step aside if he and Jefferson should tie in electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Regardless, he refused to disavow the presidency, writing in December 1800 to Representative Samuel Smith (R-MD) that he would not "engage to resign" if chosen president, adding that the question was "unnecessary, unreasonable and impertinent".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Rumors circulated that Representative James A.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard (F-DE) had—purportedly in Burr's name—approached Smith and Edward Livingston (R-NY) with offers of political appointments if they voted for Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither came to pass, however, chiefly due to Hamilton's energetic opposition to Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton embarked on a frenzied letter-writing campaign to get Federalist Representatives to support Jefferson because he was "by far not so dangerous a man" as Burr; in short, he would much rather have someone with wrong principles than someone devoid of any.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] From February 11 to 17, the House cast a total of 35 ballots; each time eight state delegations voted for Jefferson, one short of the necessary majority of nine.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On February 17, on the 36th ballot, Bayard changed his vote from Burr to no selection, joined by his allies in Maryland and Vermont.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This changed the Maryland and Vermont votes from no selection to Jefferson, giving him the votes of 10 states and the presidency.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The four representatives present from South Carolina, all Federalists, also changed their 3–1 selection of Burr to four abstentions.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Due to the experiences of this and the previous election, sentiment for a new way of selecting the president and vice president rose significantly, resulting in the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the 2015 musical *Hamilton* by Lin Manuel Miranda, the contest between Jefferson and Burr is recounted in "The Election of 1800".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The song focuses on Alexander Hamilton's role in deciding the outcome of the 1801 contingent election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The musical simplifies the complicated multiple elections somewhat, portraying Adams's unpopularity as making the real choice between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Historians wrote that Adams did not lose that badly in the original election, with the musical inflating the size of Jefferson's victory.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It implies Hamilton's support for Jefferson over Burr was the catalyst for the Burr–Hamilton duel; in fact, while that helped sour relations between Burr and Hamilton, the duel was ultimately provoked by Hamilton's statements about Burr in the 1804 New York gubernatorial election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] The **1803 United States Senate election in Massachusetts** was held in February 1803.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Incumbent Senator Jonathan Mason, who had been elected to fill the unexpired term of Benjamin Goodhue, did not run for a full term in office.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] The Massachusetts General Court deliberated and elected State Senator and former diplomat John Quincy Adams, son of former President John Adams, on the fourth ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] This is the first election in the history of the United States where the winner of the Senate in Massachusetts would eventually become president of the United States.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] This is also the first election to feature a candidate who would eventually become president of the United States.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Benjamin Goodhue was elected Senator from Massachusetts in 1796.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] However, he resigned and retired from politics in 1800.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] In his place, the legislature elected State Senator Jonathan Mason.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] When Mason's term expired in 1803, he declined to stand for re-election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] The Senate ratified the choice of Adams on a single unanimous ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Adams served one term in the Senate, though he would resign months early after the Federalist legislature prematurely voted not to award him a second term.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] Adams quickly drifted away from the Federalist Party, partly over his differences with Pickering.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1803-united-states-senate-election-in-massachusetts] After joining the Democratic-Republicans, he would go on to serve as Secretary of State and later as President of the United States from 1825 to 1829.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 1 to December 4, 1804.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party's ticket of incumbent president Thomas Jefferson and former New York governor George Clinton defeated the Federalist Party's ticket of former U.S. minister to France Charles Cotesworth Pinckney and former U.S. minister to the United Kingdom Rufus King.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election held under the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which required separate ballots for president and vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was unanimously renominated by his party's congressional nominating caucus in February; the caucus selected Clinton to succeed the outgoing vice president, Aaron Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] A "semisecret" Federalist caucus elevated Pinckney and King as the party's national candidates; while news of the caucus was widely circulated, in states where electors were chosen by popular vote, the Federalist ticket was formally unpledged.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists in several states chose not to nominate electors, resulting in a lopsided popular vote margin for Jefferson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was widely popular and considered unbeatable by many observers, following his narrow election four years earlier.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Economic prosperity, the expansion of voting rights, and the disorganized state of the opposition all benefited his campaign.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists portrayed Jefferson as a demagogue for his embrace of populist, democratic politics, and a dictator for his use of patronage and reforms to the federal judiciary.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's complicity in slavery did little to damage his candidacy even in New England, where he carried the Federalist stronghold of Massachusetts.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson won the election in a landslide, carrying every state and all but two electoral districts where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received the electoral votes of Connecticut and Delaware, where electors were appointed by the legislature, and two votes from unpledged electors in Maryland.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson polled more than 106,000 popular votes, representing 73 percent of the total, compared with fewer than 40,000 votes for the Federalist electors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent Federalist president John Adams sought re-election in 1800, but was defeated by Democratic-Republican challenger Thomas Jefferson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's running mate, Aaron Burr, was elected vice president following a contingent election in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The right to vote was widespread in the United States during the Early Republic, including the large majority of adult white men.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The expansion of voting rights during Jefferson's first term included the establishment of universal white male suffrage in Maryland in 1801.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Propertied, single women retained the right to vote in New Jersey, while Black men who met all other property and taxpaying requirements were eligible in New England, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Tennessee.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In most places, voting was by secret ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] (Kentucky and Virginia retained the English custom of oral voting.) Eligible individuals voted using paper tickets, typically handwritten, listing the voter's choice for the various offices.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Enforcement of property and taxpaying qualifications was generally lax, in part due to the frequency of land sales, which outpaced officials' ability to keep accurate records of ownership.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In other cases, local opinion or the threat of rioting might compel election officials to permit veterans and small landholders to vote when otherwise disenfranchised by state law.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Congress passed the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which was ratified by the states prior to the election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Amendment instructed the United States Electoral College to elect the president and vice president on separate ballots.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists opposed ratifying the Amendment, hoping to exploit the original electoral system to sow discord in the Democratic-Republican ranks.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] During the campaign, some Federalists encouraged the Democratic-Republican electors from New York to support Clinton for president over Jefferson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Efforts to delay ratification of the Amendment were unsuccessful, and the new system took effect in September 1804 in time for the election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson faced no internal opposition to his bid for re-election; the Democratic-Republican congressional caucus nominated him unanimously on February 25.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] With Burr out of the running, the selection of the vice-presidential candidate was the caucus's main responsibility.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] George Clinton and John Breckinridge were the leading contenders for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton had served as governor of New York for most of the last thirty years and was a veteran of the American Revolutionary War; he had received 50 electoral votes in the 1792 United States presidential election, and declined a place on the Democratic-Republican ticket in 1800.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although of advanced age, his political views aligned with Jefferson's, and he remained popular with Democratic-Republicans in his home state.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge, a Kentuckian, was the choice of Western Democratic-Republicans concerned with regional representation.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Other candidates included the U.S. attorney general, Levi Lincoln Sr.; the former U.S. senator from New Hampshire, John Langdon; and the U.S. postmaster general, Gideon Granger.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas McKean was discussed as a possible contender, but withdrew prior to the caucus.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus was attended by 110 Democratic-Republican members of Congress.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton won the nomination with 67 votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Federalists did not meet formally to nominate a ticket, as they had done in the previous election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party was ill-prepared to mount a national campaign, and few believed Jefferson could be defeated.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, a "semisecret caucus" in Washington proposed Pinckney and King as the party's national candidates on February 22.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although this meeting was widely reported, significant uncertainty persisted concerning the identities of the Federalist candidates throughout the campaign.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states where electors were chosen by popular vote, the Federalist electors remained formally unpledged.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans established a vast network of state, county, town, and ward committees to conduct the campaign.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states such as Ohio, the overriding importance of the presidential election was an agent of party unity.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republicans organized celebrations to commemorate the anniversary of Jefferson's first inauguration on March 4 and the Louisiana Purchase on May 11.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Parades, dinners, and toasting were the mainstays of such events.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Supporters sang campaign songs such as "Jefferson and Liberty," written to commemorate the last election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republican militia units, professional associations, benevolent societies, and partisan groups like the Young Men of Democratic Principles were visible supporters of the president's re-election campaign.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans made effective use of the partisan press.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party's national paper, the *National Intelligencer*, was widely circulated and supported a vast array of state and local print publications.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican campaign catered to the nation's developing white male democracy.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The abandonment of property requirements for voting in Maryland and New Jersey benefited Jefferson, whose economic policies were considered favorable to working people.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republican newspapers and broadsides were written in plain language accessible to the average person.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The themes of "simplicity and frugality" and equality of opportunity were central to the party's appeal to voters, contrasted against Federalist elitism.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In contrast to the Democratic-Republicans, the Federalists entered the campaign demoralized and to some degree leaderless.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney displayed little interest in the election and devoted most of 1804 to a local campaign against dueling.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party lost its most influential leader in July, when Alexander Hamilton was killed in a duel by the outgoing vice president, Burr.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's former deputy, Timothy Pickering, saw no hope for the presidential election and instead advocated for New England to secede from the United States.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Other Federalists simply withdrew from politics rather than endure a seemingly inevitable defeat.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard, advocated for the party to update its tactics.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The growth of mass politics in the early nineteenth century made the Federalists' reliance on elite relationships increasingly obsolete.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists held celebrations on the anniversary of Washington's birthday and organized groups like the Washington Benevolent Societies.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The effectiveness of the party press was hindered by the stilted, formal style of many Federalist newspapers.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Criticism of Jefferson, rather than enthusiasm for Pinckney, characterized the Federalist campaign.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the party nominated electors, its ticket was formally unpledged.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist press generally avoided mention of Pinckney and King; the Boston *Columbian Centinel* denied that the Federalist electors were pledged to Pinckney.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Dauer argues that the uncertainty surrounding the Federalist ticket cost the party the electoral votes of Massachusetts.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists described Jefferson as an aspiring dictator.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] They compared the Louisiana Purchase to Napoleon's European conquests and accused Jefferson of violating the Constitution, which did not specify the president's power to acquire new territory.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Increasingly, Federalists saw parallels between Jefferson's administration and the rule of European tyrants, including Napoleon, Maximilien Robespierre, and Julius Caesar.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's use of patronage and the impeachment of Samuel Chase by the House of Representatives in March 1804 were criticized by Federalists who feared Jefferson's growing influence over the political system.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The repeal of the Midnight Judges Act and the reduction of the United States Armed Forces were cast as attempts to dismantle the federal government of the United States.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's sexual relationship with Sally Hemings, an enslaved woman and the half-sister of his late wife, Martha Jefferson, was first exposed by James T.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had six children with Hemings between 1795 and 1808, although some historians argue their relationship began much earlier, during Jefferson's tenure as the U.S. minister to France.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists seized on the scandal to attack Jefferson's hypocrisy and personal character.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Partisan journals printed doggerel mocking Jefferson's promiscuity with verses that emphasized Hemings's race and complexion.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In pillorying Jefferson as an enslaver, Federalist writers did not intend to critique social inequality; instead, they sought to use Jefferson's complicity in slavery to discredit democratic politics.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists attacked Jefferson's religious views, which they described as atheism.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist ministers characterized the Democratic-Republican Party as a grave threat to Christianity.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's economic policies catered to the interests of free men and entrepreneurs, in contrast to Federalist policies that prioritized wealthy creditors.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Joyce Appleby argues that Jefferson's laissez-faire posture facilitated commercial expansion that benefited white men regardless of class.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Whereas the Federalists used economic regulation to promote the interests of creditors, Democratic-Republicans favored a decentralized economy in which opportunities to participate in commerce were more broadly accessible.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists interpreted Democratic-Republican policies as an attack on elite privilege and defended the principle of economic inequality.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although many Democratic-Republicans were skeptical of national corporations, corporations and banks flourished at the state and local level.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Both Jefferson and Pinckney were enslavers.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney played a critical role in the adoption of the Three-Fifths Clause by the Constitutional Convention and opposed the efforts to end the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson criticized slavery in print, but did little either privately or politically to diminish it; as president, he withheld diplomatic recognition from the First Empire of Haiti, the first independent state in the Americas established as the result of a successful slave rebellion.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attempted to make slavery an issue in New England, with limited success.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Both national parties sought to avoid discussion of slavery during the 1790s; after 1801, the decline of the Federalist Party in the Southern United States freed Northern Federalists to attack slavery more directly.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Antislavery rhetoric featured in some Federalists' critiques of the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] New England Federalists demanded the repeal of the Three-Fifths Clause, which disadvantaged the region in terms of congressional apportionment.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] These appeals largely failed to motivate opposition to Jefferson, while accompanying calls for secession met with little popular support.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Criticism of the Three-Fifths Clause emphasized New England Federalists' partisan self-interest.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Many Federalists blamed this provision for their defeat in the last election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Fisher Ames wrote that "black votes" had elected Jefferson in 1800 and that the administration therefore lacked a popular mandate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] New England Federalists frequently pointed to prominent Democratic-Republicans' complicity in slavery as evidence of the party's hypocrisy.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Opposing political rights for both white and Black workers, they pointed to the contradictions in Jeffersonian democracy as proof that a political system based on mass participation was unworkable.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson won the election in a landslide, carrying every state and all but two districts where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists appeared to win the popular vote on Election Day in North Carolina's Fayetteville district, but the exclusion of the return from Montgomery County, North Carolina, subsequently gave the district's single electoral vote to Jefferson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson carried Massachusetts and New Hampshire, as well as seven of nine Maryland districts.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, Jefferson carried every county except Adams, where a last-minute Federalist effort narrowly succeeded in keeping the county out of the Democratic-Republican column.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Ohio Federalists' attempt to split the Democratic-Republican Party was unsuccessful, and the Jefferson electors defeated the Federalist ticket by a wide margin.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists did not contest the remaining popular vote states, but unpledged electors received write-in votes in New Jersey and Virginia.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received electoral votes from Connecticut and Delaware, where electors were chosen by the state legislature, while Jefferson swept the remaining states for a total of 162 electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Jefferson was the first of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Henry Clay, Andrew Jackson, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, Cleveland, Roosevelt, and Trump were also their respective party's nominees for three consecutive elections.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Nineteenth-century election laws required voters to elect the members of the Electoral College individually, rather than as a block.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] This sometimes resulted in small differences in the number of votes cast for electors pledged to the same presidential nominee, if some voters did not vote for all the electors nominated by a party.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table compares the votes for the most popular elector on each ticket.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In the single-member districts in Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee, the result is the sum of all votes for electors pledged to one nominee.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, where several distinct anti-Jefferson tickets ran in different parts of the state, the result shown is the sum of the votes for the leading electors in each county.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] The **1806–07 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1806 and 1807, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] The Democratic-Republican Party increased its overwhelming control of the Senate by one additional seat.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] The Federalists went into the elections with such a small share of Senate seats (7 out of 34, or 21%) that even if they had won every election, they would still have remained a minority caucus.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] As it was, however, they lost one of the two seats they were defending and picked up no gains from their opponents.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] In these special elections, the winner was seated during 1806 or before March 4, 1807; ordered by election date.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1807; ordered by state.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] All the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] In this special election, the winner was seated in 1807 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Democratic-Republican Abraham Baldwin died March 4, 1807.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Democratic-Republican George Jones was appointed August 27.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] 1807 to continue the term, pending a special election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Jones ran in the November 7, 1807 special election, but lost to Democratic-Republican William H.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Democratic-Republican James Jackson, who had served since 1793 died March 19, 1806.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Democratic-Republican John Milledge was elected June 19, 1806.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Milledge was later re-elected to the next term.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] The Maryland General Assembly convened to both fill the unexpired term of Robert Wright who resigned to become Governor of Maryland, and to fill the next term.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] This election was therefore both the regular and special.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1806-07-united-states-senate-elections] Philip Reed won election over William Hayward by a margin of 17.50%, or 33 votes, for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 26 to December 2, 1824.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Andrew Jackson, John Quincy Adams, Henry Clay and William Crawford were the primary contenders for the presidency.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The result of the election was inconclusive, as no candidate won a majority of the electoral vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In the election for vice president, John C.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun was elected with a comfortable majority of the vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Because none of the candidates for president garnered an electoral vote majority, the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives, under the provisions of the Twelfth Amendment, held a contingent election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] On February 9, 1825, the House voted (with each state delegation casting one vote) to elect John Quincy Adams as president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party had won six consecutive presidential elections and by 1824 was the only national political party.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] However, as the election approached, the presence of multiple viable candidates resulted in there being multiple nominations by the contending factions, signaling the splintering of the party and an end to the Era of Good Feelings, as well as the First Party System.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won New England, Jackson and Adams split the mid-Atlantic states, Jackson and Clay split the Western states, and Jackson and Crawford split the Southern states.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson finished with a plurality of the popular vote (there was no popular vote in six states including New York, the most populous state), and also of the electoral vote (due to the Three-fifths Compromise), while the other three candidates each finished with a significant share of the votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Clay, who had finished fourth, was eliminated.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was the first son of a former president to become president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1800 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] It is also one of five elections in which the winner did not achieve at least a plurality of the national popular vote and the only election in which the candidate who received the most electoral votes from the Electoral College did not win the election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] It is also, to date, the election with the lowest popular vote percentage for an elected president (32.7%).
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The Era of Good Feelings, associated with the administration of President James Monroe, was a time of reduced emphasis on political party identity.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] With the Federalists discredited, Democratic-Republicans adopted some key Federalist economic programs and institutions.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] An unintended consequence of wide single-party identification was reduced party discipline.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than political harmony, factions arose within the party.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe attempted to improve discipline by appointing leading statesmen to his Cabinet, including Secretary of State John Quincy Adams of Massachusetts, Secretary of the Treasury William H.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford of Georgia, and Secretary of War John C.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] General Andrew Jackson of Tennessee led high-profile military missions.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Only House Speaker Henry Clay of Kentucky held political power independent of Monroe.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He refused to join the cabinet and remained critical of the administration.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Two key events, the Panic of 1819 and the Missouri crisis of 1820, influenced and reshaped politics.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The economic downturn broadly harmed workers, the sectional disputes over slavery expansion raised tensions, and both events plus other factors drove demand for increased democratic control.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Social disaffection would help motivate revival of rivalrous political parties in the near future, though these had not yet formed by the time of the 1824 election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The previous competition between the Federalist Party and the Democratic-Republican Party collapsed after the War of 1812 due to the disintegration of the Federalists' popular appeal.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] President James Monroe of the Democratic-Republicans was able to run effectively unopposed in the 1820 election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Like previous presidents who had been elected to two terms, Monroe declined to seek re-nomination for a third term.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The presidential nomination was thus left wide open within the Democratic-Republican Party, the only remaining major national political entity.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] During the first year of Monroe's second term, it was said that 17 names had been mentioned as possible candidates, although formal nominations did not occur until late December.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Among these possible candidates, William H.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford was seen as the most formidable, with many observers anticipating that John Quincy Adams would be his primary rival, and Henry Clay regarded as a likely outside contender.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford, a native of the Georgia frontier, was physically imposing and a powerful political figure.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He was the first president pro tem of the Senate to be elected continuingly and had nearly beaten Monroe for the party nomination in 1816.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As Secretary of the Treasury, he had helped to reorganized the nation's finances after the War of 1812 and establish the Second Bank of the United States.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As such, he came to be seen as the treasury candidate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford cultivated a strong base of support for the nomination, especially among influential political figures who could manage the congressional caucus and had, in the words of William Lowndes, his own "Organized Party" (the Old Republicans).
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Opponents accused him of consolidating power through the Tenure of Office Act of 1820, which required financial officeholders to be reappointed every four years.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In creating a web of support among self-interested agents, Crawford became a man suspected of deliberately contriving his own election, something feared by all others.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Despite these accusations, his supporters believed that he was not the conniving, maneuvering self-seeker his rivals branded him to be.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] It is impossible to know for certain, however, as little of his personal correspondence survives.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The first people to be publicly nominated as candidates were Calhoun and Lowndes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun had been clashing with Crawford since the spring of 1820, when the latter began a retrenchment campaign in response to the Panic of 1819.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun and his partisans viewed the effort as designed to emasculate the Department of War and discredit its secretary, especially as Congress failed to pass similar proposed reductions in the civil list.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun, up until this point a staunch nationalist, shared many policy positions with Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Though claiming to prefer Adams, he feared that Adams could not defeat Crawford in the Southern and Middle states.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Therefore, it fell upon him to challenge the assumption that Crawford was the favorite of the Southeast, hopefully defeating Crawford and his radicals.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Overestimating his popularity, Calhoun believed that he could build a solid core of support by appealing to the economic interests of the two most powerful states, New York and Pennsylvania, and by consolidating his home base in the Southeast.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In particular, he focused on Pennsylvania, where he made relations with the Family Party—a group of young Republican politicians in Philadelphia, led by George M.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Ingham, who opposed the state's Republican leaders that favored Crawford.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Before the nomination, he had informed Lowndes of his intention to run for president early in his stay at Calhoun's residence in Washington, which began in December 1821.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Lowndes, while having spoken positively of the other men, assured Calhoun he preferred his election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] However, during Lowndes' journey to Washington, and without his knowledge, lowcountry moderates in the South Carolina legislature made an unprecedented move by attempting to nominate Lowndes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] This effort was led by James Hamilton Jr., the Charleston delegation, and others from the tidewater parishes and Middle District counties east of the Broad River.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] They called a caucus of the legislature, which met in the hall of representatives on December 18, with about 2/3 of both houses in attendance.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Opposition to the motion consisted primarily of upcountry partisans of Calhoun who, caught off guard, argued for delay, declaring the proposal premature and condemning the very idea that a single small state should attempt to name a president for the whole nation.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] While recognizing Calhoun's credentials, Lowndes' supporters argued that he was a more nationally prominent figure who would be more acceptable to citizens across the country.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The motion to recommend Lowndes for president narrowly passed, 58 to 54, embarrassing Calhoun's campaign.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The two men agreed not to alter their plans.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun would enter the race as planned, while Lowndes would neither decline the nomination nor encourage an active campaign on his behalf, but follow the course dictated by his health.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As this would most likely result in a voyage abroad, effectively removing Lowndes from further consideration, the difficulty presented by his nomination would be resolved, and supporters could transfer their backing to Calhoun.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Despite this, his supporters remained insistent on his candidacy and encouraged him to stay.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Lowndes died on October 27, 1822, en route to a recuperative visit to England.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The next month the legislature transferred their nomination to Calhoun.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Later, in February 1824, Dallas gave his support to Jackson's presidential campaign, with Calhoun as his running mate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] While Republicans in Northern states wished to support a man of their own, many were reluctant to rally behind Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] By early 1823, critics among his supporters complained that Adams was "too fastidious and reserved," failing to engage in the political collaboration expected of a leader.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] They argued that presidents were no longer chosen purely on merit but rather through the influence of politicians and newspapers.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than endure such a leader, many potential supporters began searching for an alternative Northern candidate, though this effort ultimately proved fruitless.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Rufus King was too old and also unwilling.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Tompkins had long-since been dismissed as a viable successor to Monroe due to a combination of health problems and a financial dispute with the federal government, and he formally ruled himself out of making a presidential run at the start of 1824.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Secretary of the Navy Smith Thompson, believing his New York ties might make him a viable option, delayed accepting a seat on the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Supreme Court for eight months before being persuaded that he stood no chance of the presidency.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, while having been supported by a small minority for president in 1820, suffered from the memory of his past involvements with Federalists, and in 1822 had become too electorally weak to compete, let alone win New York presidentially against the state's political machine.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The *Niles' Weekly Register*, reporting on Washington politics in its January 26, 1822, issue, reported the names of Calhoun, Thompson, Clinton, Lowndes, Tompkins, Adams, Clay, and Crawford as being put forth as candidates.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The newspaper also reported that "one or two others are casually spoken of" but did not identify them.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Lowndes' nomination had sparked intense speculation in Washington during the first week of the new year, concerned with the ramifications of the way Lowndes had been nominated.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In a letter to his wife, Lowndes stated, "The House is in terrible confusion.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] I thought when I came here that the question was in fact confined to two persons Mr Crawford and Mr Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] That year, Kentucky and Missouri legislature caucuses nominated Clay, and Tennessee nominated Jackson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In January 1823, a meeting of Ohio legislators approved resolutions naming Clay.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In early 1823, the legislatures of Massachusetts and Maine stated a preference for Adams but did not make a formal nomination, as they wished to ensure party unity nationwide.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In January 1824, a caucus in the Mississippi legislature divided evenly between supporting Adams and Jackson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In Rhode Island, the "State Junta" initially committed itself in early 1824 to supporting the caucus candidate but soon realized they could not sway public opinion against Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Consequently, they refrained from pressing for Crawford out of fear of jeopardizing their state ticket.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In early 1824, the Connecticut legislature nominated Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In March 1824, a state party convention at Harrisburg nominated Jackson.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In June 1824, the New Hampshire legislature nominated Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The legislatures of Maine, New York, Virginia, and Georgia were in favor of the Congressional nominating caucus.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] While not always popular, in past elections the party had relied on a congressional caucus, sometimes referred to as the "King Caucus," to nominate their presidential candidates, a process that had consistently succeeded in identifying the party favorite.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Now, however, there was no certainty that the caucus would work again.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Proponents, many of whom supported William H.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford, argued that it was essential for maintaining the stability of the republic and ensuring party unity on the presidential question.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Opponents, including some of Crawford's own supporters, criticized the process as limiting the people's choice and effectively predetermining the outcome of the popular election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The strongest opposition came from Jacksonians.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] They viewed it as emblematic of the insider manipulation they sought to dismantle.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] On the other hand, New England Republicans, drawn to traditional party practices, had no such objection, and about 20 were believed to be willing to support Crawford if they could not have Adams, until Adams declared he would not accept a nomination for any office from a congressional caucus.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In most delegations there were one or two representatives who, if left to themselves, were willing to attend the caucus.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford hoped to secure more than the 65 ballots that Monroe had obtained in 1816.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In early February 1824, a majority of congressmen signed a public statement that they would not attend a nominating caucus.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] They believed that by refusing to attend instead of killing it, the caucus system would collapse on its own.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Gallatin had not sought the vice presidential nomination and soon withdrew at Crawford's request.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Gallatin was also dissatisfied with repeated attacks on his credibility made by the other candidates.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He was replaced by North Carolina senator Nathaniel Macon.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams sought to have Jackson be his vice-presidential running mate and Louisa Adams hosted a ball in honor of the Battle of New Orleans' ninth anniversary.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He had supported Jackson during his invasion of Florida while Clay and Crawford opposed him, causing Jackson to oppose them.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Clay supporters in the Tennessee legislature nominated Jackson for president in 1822, as an attempt to weaken Crawford in the state.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Martin Van Buren and his political machine supported Crawford in New York.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] During the selection of New York's electors Van Buren was able to deny Clay enough support to prevent him from being eligible for the contingent election.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] All four candidates were nominated by at least one state legislature.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Andrew Jackson was recruited to run for the office of the president by the state legislature of Tennessee.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson did not seek the task of running for president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, he wished to retire to his estate on the outskirts of Nashville, called the Hermitage.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates drew voter support by different states and sections.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams dominated the popular vote in New England and won some support elsewhere, Clay dominated his home state of Kentucky and won pluralities in two neighboring states, and Crawford won the Virginia vote overwhelmingly and polled well in North Carolina.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had geographically the broadest support, though there were heavy vote concentrations in his home state of Tennessee and in Pennsylvania and populous areas where even he ran poorly.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Policy played a reduced role in the election, though positions on tariffs and internal improvements did create significant disagreements.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Both Adams and Jackson supporters backed Secretary of War John C.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun of South Carolina for vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] He easily secured the majority of electoral votes for that office.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The campaigning for presidential election of 1824 took many forms.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Contrafacta, or well known songs and tunes whose lyrics have been altered, were used to promote political agendas and presidential candidates.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Below can be found a sound clip featuring "Hunters of Kentucky", a tune written by Samuel Woodsworth in 1815 under the title "The Unfortunate Miss Bailey".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Contrafacta such as this one, which promoted Andrew Jackson as a national hero, have been a long-standing tradition in presidential elections.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Another form of campaigning during this election was through newsprint.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Political cartoons and partisan writings were best circulated among the voting public through newspapers.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun was one of the candidates most directly involved through his participation in the publishing of the newspaper *The Patriot* as a member of the editorial staff.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] This was a sure way to promote his own political agendas and campaign.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In contrast, most candidates involved in early 19th century elections did not run their own political campaigns.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Instead it was left to volunteer citizens and partisans to speak on their behalf.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The 1824 presidential election marked the final collapse of the Republican-Federalist political framework.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The electoral map confirmed the candidates' sectional support, with Adams winning in New England, Jackson having wide voter appeal, Clay attracting votes from the West, and Crawford attracting votes from the eastern South.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson earned only a plurality of electoral votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the presidential election was decided by the House of Representatives, which elected John Quincy Adams on the first ballot.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun, supported by Adams and Jackson, easily won the vice presidency, not requiring a contingent election in the Senate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's electoral college plurality was the result of the Three-fifths Compromise.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The electoral college results would have been 83 for Adams and 77 for Jackson without the inflated electoral count of slaveholding states.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern-day presidential elections.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who a particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given candidate.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Jackson electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Jackson would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As no presidential candidate had won an absolute electoral vote majority, the responsibility for electing a new president devolved upon the U.S.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives, which held a contingent election on February 9, 1825.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] As prescribed by the Twelfth Amendment, the House was limited to choosing from among the three candidates who received the most electoral votes: Andrew Jackson, John Quincy Adams, and William Crawford; Henry Clay, who had finished fourth, was eliminated.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Each state delegation, voting *en bloc*, had a single vote.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] There were 24 states at the time, thus an absolute majority of 13 votes was required for victory.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Even if Clay had wished to align with Crawford over Jackson, which was highly unlikely in any event since Clay's policy differences with Crawford were even deeper, especially on matters of the tariff, Crawford had been in poor health, and no path to victory was evident.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Daniel Pope Cook, Illinois' sole representative, was anti-slavery and gave his support to Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] James Buchanan attempted to make a compromise with Clay in which Jackson would make him Secretary of State in exchange for his support.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Clay instead gave his support to Adams and was able to have the Kentucky, Missouri, and Ohio delegations support him.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Illinois, Louisiana, and Maryland, which Jackson won during the election, had their delegations support Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren attempted to have New York's delegation be divided between Adams and Crawford in order to increase its power and make a deal with one of them.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] However, Stephen Van Rensselaer, a Federalist allied with Van Buren, voted for Adams.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren stated that Van Rensselaer found a ballot for Adams on the floor while Van Rensselaer, in his letter to Governor DeWitt Clinton, stated that he voted for Adams as he was bound to win and that he wanted to shorten "the long agony".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren supported Jackson during the 1828 election and aided in Calhoun's selection as vice president.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Ignoring the nonbinding directive of the Kentucky legislature that its House delegation choose Jackson, the delegation voted 8–4 for Adams instead.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, Adams was elected president on the first ballot, with 13 states, followed by Jackson with seven, and Crawford with four.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' victory shocked Jackson, who, as the winner of a plurality of both the popular and electoral votes, expected the House to choose him.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Not long before the contingent House election, an anonymous statement appeared in a Philadelphia paper, called the *Columbian Observer*.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] The statement, said to be from a member of Congress, essentially accused Clay of selling Adams his support for the office of Secretary of State.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] No formal investigation was conducted, so the matter was neither confirmed nor denied.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] When Clay was indeed offered the position after Adams was victorious, he opted to accept and continue to support the administration he voted for, knowing that declining the position would not have helped to dispel the rumors brought against him.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson referred to Clay as the "Judas of the West".
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] By appointing Clay his Secretary of State, President Adams essentially declared him heir to the presidency, as Adams and his three predecessors had all served as Secretary of State.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson and his followers accused Adams and Clay of striking a "corrupt bargain", and the Jacksonians would campaign on this claim for the next four years, ultimately helping Jackson defeat Adams in 1828.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Ironically, Adams offered Jackson a position in his Cabinet as Secretary of War, which Jackson declined to accept.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives after the 1824–25 elections and obtained the speakership for John W.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' relationship with Calhoun deteriorated, with Calhoun opposing Clay's appointment as Secretary of State due to his own presidential ambitions.
[src:1824-united-states-presidential-election/1824-united-states-presidential-election] In June 1826, Calhoun gave his support to Jackson for the 1828 election.
